<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Signs WIPO Trademark Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Signs WIPO Trademark Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0605045794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0439 GMT 6 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0605045794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, May 5 (XINHUA) -- China joined the Nice 
agreement of the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) 
on Thursday [5 May] to internationalize its trademark system. 
  The agreement, known as "The Agreement on the International 
Classification of Goods and Services for Trademark 
Registration," was first established in 1957 and is the major 
instrument of WIPO. 
  Tang Yufeng, deputy representative of the Chinese mission to 
the UN in Geneva, presented a protocol for entry to Arpad 
Bogsch, director-general of WIPO. 
  Since joining WIPO in 1980, China has signed nearly all 
international agreements protecting intellectual property rights. 
  Bogsch said that a special meeting will be held for the 
entry 
of Chinese products into international trademark registration. 
  The Nice agreement now has 36 signatory members. 

</TEXT>

